\section{Deferred values}{


Asynchronous computation is represented by deferred values.
A deferred value is an \href{https://github.com/wch/R6}{R6} object.\preformatted{deferred$new(action = NULL, on_progress = NULL, on_cancel = NULL,
   parents = NULL, parent_resolve = NULL, parent_reject = NULL,
   type = NULL)
}

Creates a new deferred value. \code{action} is a function that is called
once the deferred value is \emph{started} (i.e. \emph{not} when \code{dx} is created).
It must have one or two arguments: \code{resolve}, or \code{resolve} and \code{progress}
It should call \code{resolve} when it is done, with the final value of the
deferred as the argument. (See examples below.) If it has two arguments,
then the second one is a callback function for creating progress bars.
The deferred value may report its progress through this function.
See details in the \emph{Progress bars} section below.

\code{action} is called when the evaluation of the deferred value is started.
Only deferred values that are needed to calculate the value of the
async phase, are evaluated. (See also \emph{Lazy Evaluation} below.)

Note that \code{action} is optional, for some deferred values, no action is
takes when they are started. (These typically depend on their parent
nodes.)

\code{on_cancel} is a function that is called without arguments when a
deferred value is cancelled. This includes explicit cancellation by
calling its \code{$cancel()} method, or auto-cancellation (see below).

\code{parents} is a list of deferred values that need to be computed before
the current deferred value. When a parent deferred is resolved, the
\code{parent_resolve} function is called. When a parent referred throws an
error, the parent_reject` function is called.

\code{parent_resolve} is a function with (up to) three arguments:
\code{value}, \code{resolve} and \code{id}. It will be called with the value of the
parent, the \code{resolve} callback of the deferred, and the id of the parent.
