\section{Control flow helper functions}{


Control flow with deferred values can be challenging. Some helpers:
\itemize{
\item \code{\link[=async_reflect]{async_reflect()}} creates an async function that always succeeds.
This is useful if you want to apply it to a collection, and don't
want to stop at the first error.
\item \code{\link[=async_retry]{async_retry()}} tries an async function a number of times.
\code{\link[=async_retryable]{async_retryable()}} turns a regular function into a retryable one.
\item \code{\link[=async_sequence]{async_sequence()}} chains two async functions. Calling their sequence
is equivalent calling '$then()` on them, but \code{\link[=async_sequence]{async_sequence()}} is
easier to use programmatically.
\item \code{\link[=async_until]{async_until()}} and \code{\link[=async_whilst]{async_whilst()}} let you call an async function
repeatedly, until or while a (syncronous) condition holds.
\item \code{\link[=async_timeout]{async_timeout()}} runs an async function with a timeout.
}
}

